psutil — Cross-platform process and system utilities (Cygwin port)

Upstream: https://github.com/giampaolo/psutil
Version:  7.1.0
License:  BSD-3-Clause

Patch summary (47 files):

  Platform implementation (new):
    psutil/_pscygwin.py
        Cygwin platform module (Python wrapper over _psutil_cygwin).
        Imports _psutil_cygwin as cext, defines Cygwin-specific named
        tuples, implements process and system APIs using /proc and
        selective Win32 calls via iphlpapi.dll.

    psutil/_psutil_cygwin.c
        C extension entry point. Unlike other POSIX platforms, Cygwin
        does NOT build a separate _psutil_posix extension — POSIX
        functionality is included directly in this extension for
        isolation.

    psutil/arch/cygwin/*.c, *.h
        Subsystem implementation files (cpu, disk, io, mem, net,
        net_connections, proc, system) plus win32.c for selective
        Windows API calls and win32_apis.c for Win32→Python exception
        translation (ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED → PermissionError → AccessDenied).

    psutil/arch/cygwin/posix/*.h, posix_compat.h, posix_wrappers/*.c
        POSIX header shims and wrapper files that bridge Cygwin's
        POSIX layer to the places where upstream psutil expects
        Linux-style /proc semantics.

  Cross-platform dispatch (modified):
    psutil/__init__.py
        Add Cygwin platform detection and module dispatch.

    psutil/_common.py
        Add CYGWIN constant for platform checks.

    psutil/arch/all/init.h
        Shared C init header update for the Cygwin build.

  Build system:
    setup.py
        Cygwin detection via sys.platform and PATH. Adds PSUTIL_CYGWIN
        macro, -std=gnu99, and the arch/cygwin/ source list. Unlike
        other POSIX platforms, Cygwin does NOT build the separate
        _psutil_posix extension.

    Makefile
        Cygwin platform detection for the test-platform target.

    .gitattributes, .gitignore
        Line ending normalization and build-artifact ignores.

  Scripts:
    scripts/disk_usage.py   Handle PermissionError on inaccessible drives
    scripts/procsmem.py     Add Cygwin to supported platform check

  Regression tests (9 files):
    psutil/tests/__init__.py              2x GLOBAL_TIMEOUT; PYTHONPATH for subprocs
    psutil/tests/test_cygwin.py           New Cygwin-specific test file
    psutil/tests/test_connections.py      Skip UNIX socket enumeration
    psutil/tests/test_contracts.py        Cygwin contract branches
    psutil/tests/test_process.py          Cygwin process-test branches
    psutil/tests/test_process_all.py      ionice validation (Linux convention)
    psutil/tests/test_system.py           Cygwin system-test branches
    psutil/tests/test_testutils.py        Skip UNIX socketpair
    psutil/tests/test_unicode.py          Skip UNIX socket enumeration

Build notes:

  The C extension is built with -std=gnu99 and the PSUTIL_CYGWIN macro.
  Unlike other POSIX platforms, no separate _psutil_posix extension is
  built — POSIX functionality is included directly in _psutil_cygwin
  for isolation from the Cygwin-specific subsystem code.

  The port is a hybrid: POSIX APIs consistently for sockets and process
  enumeration (via /proc), selective Windows APIs (iphlpapi, psapi) for
  network connections and Windows-accurate memory metrics where
  /proc/<pid>/status doesn't match Windows counters.

Known limitations:

  UNIX socket enumeration:
    Cygwin's /proc/net/unix does not expose UNIX-domain sockets, so
    net_connections(kind='unix') returns empty. Affected upstream tests
    are skipped on Cygwin.

  Process iteration is slower than Linux:
    Each /proc/<pid>/stat read crosses the Cygwin POSIX/Win32 boundary.
    GLOBAL_TIMEOUT is doubled on Cygwin in the test infrastructure.

  DLL rebase after build:
    The Cygwin extension DLL must sometimes be rebased after build to
    avoid fork() address space collisions. Run 'rebaseall' if fork
    failures appear in the test suite.

Runtime dependency chain:

    psutil <- pypinfo <- grpcio <- protobuf <- abseil-cpp

psutil sits at the root of the phdye-cygwin Python dependency chain —
pypinfo depends on it; grpcio depends on pypinfo transitively via the
Cygwin port effort.

Source: https://github.com/phdye-cygwin/psutil, branch cygwin/v7.1.0
